description: Contains data elements for Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA) [Examples of CDEs included: Sitting down; Sitting balance]

cdes.cdeName: Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA) - balance seated score
cdes.definitionDescription: Score to report semiquantitative assessment for the ability of the participant/subject to maintain balance while seated in a hard armless chair for the Tinetti Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA)
cdes.permissibleDescription: Unable to maintain position (marked slide forward or leans forward or to side);Leans or slides in chair;Steady, safe, upright;
cdes.instructions: Refer to instructions on form.
cdes.referrences: Tinetti ME. Performance-oriented assessment of mobility problems in elderly patients. J Am Geriatr Soc. 1986 Feb;34(2):119-26.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA) - balance arise score
cdes.definitionDescription: Score to report semiquantitative assessment for the ability of the participant/subject to maintain balance when arising from a hard armless chair for the Tinetti Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA)
cdes.permissibleDescription: 0 = Unable without help;1 = Able, but uses arm to help;2 = Able without use of arms;
cdes.instructions: Refer to instructions on form.
cdes.referrences: Tinetti ME. Performance-oriented assessment of mobility problems in elderly patients. J Am Geriatr Soc. 1986 Feb;34(2):119-26.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA) - balance attempt arise score
cdes.definitionDescription: Score to report semiquantitative assessment for the ability of the participant/subject to maintain balance when attempting to arise from a hard armless chair for the Tinetti Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA)
cdes.permissibleDescription: 0 = Unable without help;1 = Able, but requires more than one attempt;2 = Able to arise with one attempt;
cdes.instructions: Refer to instructions on form.
cdes.referrences: Tinetti ME. Performance-oriented assessment of mobility problems in elderly patients. J Am Geriatr Soc. 1986 Feb;34(2):119-26.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA) - balance immediate stand score
cdes.definitionDescription: Score to report semiquantitative assessment for the ability of the participant/subject to maintain standing balance immediately after arising from a hard armless chair for the Tinetti Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA)
cdes.permissibleDescription: 0 = Unsteady (staggers, moves feet, marked trunk sway);1 = Steady but uses walker or cane or grabs other object for support;2 = Steady without walker or cane or other support;
cdes.instructions: First 5 seconds.
cdes.referrences: Tinetti ME. Performance-oriented assessment of mobility problems in elderly patients. J Am Geriatr Soc. 1986 Feb;34(2):119-26.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA) - balance stand score
cdes.definitionDescription: Score to report semiquantitative assessment for the ability of the participant/subject to maintain balance when standing for the Tinetti Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA)
cdes.permissibleDescription: 0 = Unsteady;1 = Steady, but with wide stance (medial heels more than 4 inches apart) or uses cane, walker or other support;2 = Narrow stance without support;
cdes.instructions: Refer to instructions on form.
cdes.referrences: Tinetti ME. Performance-oriented assessment of mobility problems in elderly patients. J Am Geriatr Soc. 1986 Feb;34(2):119-26.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA) - balance nudge score
cdes.definitionDescription: Score to report semiquantitative assessment for the ability of the participant/subject to maintain balance while standing when a sternal nudge is applied for the Tinetti Performance-Oriented Mobility Assessment (POMA)
cdes.permissibleDescription: 0 = Begins to fall;1 = Staggers, grabs, but catches self;2 = Steady;
cdes.instructions: Subject at maximum position with feet as close together as possible. Examiner pushes lightly on subject's sternum with palm of hand 3 times.

description: Physical and Neurological Examination for Subtle Signs (PANESS)

The physical exam is generally administered at screening and/or baseline to determine study eligibility. It may also be administered at follow-up visits to track a participant's/subject's physical status. This CRF Module captures the physical exam results.

cdes.cdeName: Physical exam date and time
cdes.definitionDescription: Date (and time if applicable and known) physical exam was performed
cdes.instructions: Record the date (and time) the physical exam was performed. Record the date/time according to the ISO 8601, the International Standard for the representation of dates and times (http://www.iso.org/iso/home.html).  The date/time should be recorded to the level of granularity known (e.g., year, year and month, complete date plus hours and minutes, etc.).
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: EVAL_DT

description: Contains data elements that describe the results of a physical/ neurological examination of the study participant/ subject following the stroke event. (Examples of CDEs included: elements from the NIH Stroke Scale; MMSE total score; and elements from the Scandinavian Stroke Scale)

cdes.cdeName: Data collected date and time
cdes.definitionDescription: Date (and time, if applicable and known) the data were collected. This may be the date/time a particular examination or procedure was performed.
cdes.instructions: Record the date/time according to the ISO 8601, the International Standard for the representation of dates and times (http://www.iso.org/iso/home.html).  The date/time should be recorded to the level of granularity known (e.g., year, year and month, complete date plus hours and minutes, etc.).
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE) - total score
cdes.definitionDescription: Total score for the Mini-Mental State Examination (MMSE).  The MMSE is a brief, quantitative measure of cognitive status in adults. It can be used to screen for cognitive impairment, to estimate the severity of cognitive impairment at a given point in time, to follow the course of cognitive changes in an individual over time, and to document an individual's response to treatment.  The MMSE has demonstrated validity and reliability in psychiatric, neurologic, geriatric, and other medical populations.
cdes.instructions:
Despite the many free versions of the test that are available on the internet, the official versions are copyrighted and must be ordered through the publisher:
MMSE- version 1: http://www3.parinc.com/products/product.aspx?Productid=MMSE
MMSE- version 2: http://www.minimental.com/
cdes.referrences:
Crum RM, Anthony JC, Bassett SS, Folstein MF. Population-based norms for the mini-mental state examination by age and educational level. JAMA. 1993;269(18):2386-2391.
Folstein MF, Folstein SE, McHugh PR.  Mini-mental state : a practical method for grading the cognitive state of patients for the clinician. J Psychiatr Res. 1975;12:189-198.
Tombaugh TN, McIntyre NJ. The mini-mental state examination: a comprehensive review. J Am Geriatr Soc. 1992;40(9):922-935.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Consciousness findings result
cdes.definitionDescription: Assess consciousness using the Scandinavian Stroke Scale
cdes.permissibleDescription: Fully conscious;Somnolent, can be awaked to full consciousness;Reacts to verbal command, but is not fully conscious;
cdes.instructions: The points associated with the permissible values may be less relevant when the entire Scandinavian Stroke Scale is not being used. This would be an alternative to the NIHSS LOC Items.
cdes.referrences: Multicenter trial of hemodilution in ischemic stroke--background and study protocol. Scandinavian Stroke Study Group. Stroke 1985 Sep-Oct; 16(5):885-90.

cdes.cdeName: Hand strength findings result
cdes.definitionDescription: Assess hand strength/ motor power on the affected side using the Scandinavian Stroke Scale
cdes.permissibleDescription: Normal strength;Reduced strength in full range;Some movement, fingertips do not reach palm;Paralysis;
cdes.instructions: The points associated with the permissible values may be less relevant when the entire Scandinavian Stroke Scale is not being used.
cdes.referrences: Multicenter trial of hemodilution in ischemic stroke--background and study protocol. Scandinavian Stroke Study Group. Stroke 1985 Sep-Oct; 16(5):885-90.

cdes.cdeName: Hand function findings result
cdes.definitionDescription: Assess hand function on the affected side using the Orgogozo Stroke Scale
cdes.permissibleDescription: Normal - No restriction upon the performance of any movement , even if there is a minimal weakness;Skilled - Restriction of fine movements. The more complex movements are impaired, but there is no restriction upon the performance of common, daily-life movements, even if these are executed slowly or clumsily , antagonistic movements between finger and thumb possible;Useful - Gross movements possible. Delicate movements cannot be performed, but patient can handle and carry objects of at least match-box size, use a fork or a pencil in approximate fashion, can handle a cane or grip a hand rail;Useless - Useful movements impossible. Patient cannot hold or carry objects, even if some elementary movements can be performed.;
cdes.instructions: Numeric scores may not be needed if the full Orgogozo Stroke Scale is not administered.
cdes.referrences: Orgogozo JM, Capildeo R.  Development of a neurological score for clinical evaluation of infarctions in the Sylvian territory.  Presse Med 1983:12(48):3039-44.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Upper limb tone findings result
cdes.definitionDescription: Assess tone of upper limbs on the affected side using the Orgogozo Stroke Scale
cdes.permissibleDescription: Normal - Near Normal. No frank hypertonia or hypotonia in comparison with the healthy side, even if the jerk reflexes are exaggerated;Overtly spastic or flaccid - Frank hypertonia or hypotonia in comparison with the healthy side. Permanent rigidity, or flexion or extension induced by painful stimuli.;
cdes.instructions: Numeric scores may not be needed if the full Orgogozo Stroke Scale is not administered.
cdes.referrences: Orgogozo JM, Capildeo R.  Development of a neurological score for clinical evaluation of infarctions in the Sylvian territory.  Presse Med 1983:12(48):3039-44.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

Permanent rigidity, or flexion or extension induced by painful stimuli.;
cdes.instructions: Numeric scores may not be needed if the full Orgogozo Stroke Scale is not administered.

description: The Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index is a self-rated questionnaire that primarily assesses nighttime sleep problems. It focuses on sleep experiences over the past month. It has 19 self-rated questions and 5 additional questions for a bed partner or roommate.

cdes.cdeName: Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) - Bed past month time
cdes.definitionDescription: The bed time (recorded as 24-hour clock or military time) for the majority of the nights in the past month, as part of the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI).
cdes.questionText: During the past month, what time have you usually gone to bed at night?
cdes.instructions: Use 24-hour clock (military time) to record. The following questions relate to the subject's usual sleep habits during the past month only. Answers should indicate the most accurate reply for the majority of days and nights in the past month. Must answer all questions.

cdes.cdeName: Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) - Sleep latency scale
cdes.definitionDescription: The scale to which sleep latency was calculated, as part of the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI).
cdes.instructions:
Q2 corresponds to PSQIFallAsleepPastMonthScl , Q5a correspons to PSQINoSleepIn30minPastMonthScl. First, recode Q2 into Q2new thusly:
IF Q2 > 0 and < 15, THEN set value of Q2new to 0
IF Q2 > 15 and < 30, THEN set value of Q2new to 1
IF Q2 > 30 and < 60, THEN set value of Q2new to 2
IF Q2 > 60, THEN set value of Q2new to 3 next IF Q5a + Q2new = 0, THEN set value to 0
IF Q5a + Q2new > 1 and < 2, THEN set value to 1
IF Q5a + Q2new > 3 and < 4, THEN set value to 2
IF Q5a + Q2new > 5 and < 6, THEN set value to 3

cdes.cdeName: Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) - Sleep latency scale
cdes.definitionDescription: The scale to which sleep latency was calculated, as part of the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI).
cdes.instructions:
Q2 corresponds to PSQIFallAsleepPastMonthScl , Q5a correspons to PSQINoSleepIn30minPastMonthScl. First, recode Q2 into Q2new thusly:
IF Q2 > 0 and < 15, THEN set value of Q2new to 0
IF Q2 > 15 and < 30, THEN set value of Q2new to 1
IF Q2 > 30 and < 60, THEN set value of Q2new to 2
IF Q2 > 60, THEN set value of Q2new to 3 next IF Q5a + Q2new = 0, THEN set value to 0
IF Q5a + Q2new > 1 and < 2, THEN set value to 1
IF Q5a + Q2new > 3 and < 4, THEN set value to 2
IF Q5a + Q2new > 5 and < 6, THEN set value to 3

description: The Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index is a self-rated questionnaire that primarily assesses nighttime sleep problems. It focuses on sleep experiences over the past month. It has 19 self-rated questions and 5 additional questions for a bed partner or roommate.

cdes.cdeName: Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) - Bed past month time
cdes.definitionDescription: The bed time (recorded as 24-hour clock or military time) for the majority of the nights in the past month, as part of the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI).
cdes.questionText: During the past month, what time have you usually gone to bed at night?
cdes.instructions: Use 24-hour clock (military time) to record. The following questions relate to the subject's usual sleep habits during the past month only. Answers should indicate the most accurate reply for the majority of days and nights in the past month. Must answer all questions.

cdes.cdeName: Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) - Fall asleep past month minute scale
cdes.definitionDescription: The scaled duration of time (in minutes) it takes the subject to fall asleep the majority of the nights in the past month, as part of the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI).
cdes.questionText: During the past month, how long (in minutes) has it usually taken you to fall asleep each night?
cdes.permissibleDescription: Greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to 15;Greater than 15 and less than or equal to 30;Greater than 30 and less than or equal to 60;Greater than 60;
cdes.instructions:
The following questions relate to the subject's usual sleep habits during the past month only. Answers should indicate the most accurate reply for the majority of days and nights in the past month. Must answer all questions. IF Q4 > 7, THEN set value to 0

cdes.cdeName: Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) - Sleep efficiency scale
cdes.definitionDescription: The sleep efficiency scale calculated, as part of the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI).
cdes.permissibleDescription: Greater than or equal to 85;Less than 85 and greater than or equal to 75;Less than 75 and greater than or equal to 65;Less than 65;
cdes.instructions: Calculate the hours between bed time (PSQIBedPastMonthTime) and wake up time (PSQIWakeUpPastMonthTime). Divide PSQIActSleepPastMonthScl to the calculated number and multiply by 100. This number will then be coded: 85 or greater= 0, Less than 85 and greater than or equal to 75= 1, Less than 75 and greater than or equal to 65= 2, Less than 65= 3

cdes.cdeName: Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) - Sleep latency scale
cdes.definitionDescription: The scale to which sleep latency was calculated, as part of the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI).
cdes.instructions:
Q2 corresponds to PSQIFallAsleepPastMonthScl , Q5a correspons to PSQINoSleepIn30minPastMonthScl. First, recode Q2 into Q2new thusly:
IF Q2 > 0 and < 15, THEN set value of Q2new to 0
IF Q2 > 15 and < 30, THEN set value of Q2new to 1
IF Q2 > 30 and < 60, THEN set value of Q2new to 2
IF Q2 > 60, THEN set value of Q2new to 3 next IF Q5a + Q2new = 0, THEN set value to 0
IF Q5a + Q2new > 1 and < 2, THEN set value to 1
IF Q5a + Q2new > 3 and < 4, THEN set value to 2
IF Q5a + Q2new > 5 and < 6, THEN set value to 3

crfModuleGuideline: Post Acute Care Admission Continuity Assessment Record and Evaluation (PAC Admission CARE) Tool - Section VI: Functional Status
description: Post Acute Care Admission Continuity Assessment Record and Evaluation (PAC Admission CARE) Tool - Section VI: Functional Status
Describes the status of the participant/subject at selected time points following discharge from the hospital.

cdes.cdeName: Vital status
cdes.definitionDescription: Status of participant/subject as alive or dead
cdes.instructions: Choose one.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Return work school status
cdes.definitionDescription: Status of participant's/subject's return to work and/or school
cdes.questionText: Return to work or school (choose one):
cdes.permissibleValue: Returned to previous level;Same work or school, reduced level;Different work or school;Only in sheltered environment;Did not return to work or school;N/A;Unknown;
cdes.permissibleDescription: Returned to previous level;Same work or school, reduced level;Different work or school;Only in sheltered environment;Did not return to work or school;N/A;Unknown;
cdes.instructions: Choose one. Recommend collection at least at end of initial medical care. Add date stamp for when assessed.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined
cdes.previousTitle: Return to work or school status
